{TEXT 271 97 "What was the common theme of the above three sets of cal
culations for different pairs of numbers?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 147 "Use the Fundamental Theorem of Ar
ithmetic to provide a written argument to verify the general formula t
hat for any pair of positive integers (m,n):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 34 "         mn = gcd(m,n) * lcm(m,
n)." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 7 "m:=50:\n" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 7 "
n:=200:" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "ifactor(gcd(m,n)
*lcm(m,n));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&)-%!G6#\"\"#\"\"%\"\"
\")-F&6#\"\"&F)F*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "gcd(m,n
);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"#]" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "lcm(m,n);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"$+#" 
}}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 
0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 7 "50*200;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"&++
\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "ifactor(10000);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&)-%!G6#\"\"#\"\"%\"\"\")-F&6#\"\"&F)
F*" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 274 16 "Argument: 50,200" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }{TEXT 293 2 "kp" }
{TEXT -1 30 " why do the formula hold??  -1" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 198 "8.   Numerical Approximations.
  While Maple can perform exact arithmetic, there are times when it is
 important or helpful to obtain a decimal approximation for some exact
 answer.  For instance, the " }{TEXT 275 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 66 " comm
and can be used to find the \"exact\" roots of the polynomial  " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p := x^3-11*x^2-70*x+600;" "6#>%\"pG,**$%\"xG\"\"$\"\"
\"*&\"#6F)*$F'\"\"#F)!\"\"*&\"#qF)F'F)F.\"$+'F)" }{TEXT -1 34 " .  Exe
cute the following command:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 33 "x:=80:\nsqrt(x^3-11*x^2-70*x+600);
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,$*&\"#5\"\"\"\"%mV#F&\"\"#F&" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 289 "That isn
't very illuminating.  It maybe hard to tell, but there are three root
s.  If you change the problem slightly, it may be even harder.  (For e
xample, change the number 70 in the above problem to 80 and then do th
e calculation!)  To display each root separately, execute the commands
:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 24 "r1 := Re(roots_of_p[1]);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#r1G\"'cM7" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
24 "r2 := Re(roots_of_p[2]);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#r2G
-%#ReG6#&%+roots_of_pG6#\"\"#" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 24 "r3 := Re(roots_of_p[3]);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#r
3G-%#ReG6#&%+roots_of_pG6#\"\"$" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 47 "Even that isn't all that helpful.  The co
mmand " }{TEXT 276 5 "evalf" }{TEXT -1 187 "  which stands for \"evalu
ate using floating point\" can be used to give a decimal approximation
 of an value.  The number of decimal places can be specified.  Execute
 the following command:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 20 "r1:=432169871592228:" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "evalf(r1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+;()p@V\"\"&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "r2:=123456:" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "evalf(r2);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"'cM7\"\"!" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 10 "evalf(r3);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 98 "With these last computations,  we at least have a feel \+
for the general location of the roots of p." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 199 "To obtain a feel for what \"floating point arithmetic\" means,
